which in particular shows that the map formula_232 is continuous.

Given two subsets formula_36 and formula_234 of formula_15, we define their Hausdorff distance to be

In general, the Hausdorff distance formula_238 can be infinite. Two sets are close to each other in the Hausdorff distance if every element of either set is close to some element of the other set.

The Hausdorff distance formula_239 turns the set formula_240 of all non-empty compact subsets of formula_15 into a metric space. One can show that formula_240 is complete if formula_15 is complete.

One can then define the Gromov–Hausdorff distance between any two metric spaces by considering the minimal Hausdorff distance of isometrically embedded versions of the two spaces. Using this distance, the class of all (isometry classes of) compact metric spaces becomes a metric space in its own right.

If formula_244 are metric spaces, and formula_245 is the Euclidean norm on formula_246, then formula_247 is a metric space, where the product metric is defined by

and the induced topology agrees with the product topology. By the equivalence of norms in finite dimensions, an equivalent metric is obtained if formula_245 is the taxicab norm, a p-norm, the maximum norm, or any other norm which is non-decreasing as the coordinates of a positive formula_87-tuple increase (yielding the triangle inequality).

Similarly, a countable product of metric spaces can be obtained using the following metric

An uncountable product of metric spaces need not be metrizable. For example, formula_252 is not first-countable and thus isn't metrizable.

In the case of a single space formula_14, the distance map formula_254 (from the definition) is uniformly continuous with respect to any of the above product metrics formula_255, and in particular is continuous with respect to the product topology of formula_256.

